Title: Welcome to the ER: Please Take a Number\
You wake up feeling like a team of ninjas has been stabbing you in the belly all night. The pain is relentless \'97 twisting, bloating, pulsing \'97 and you can\'92t tell if it\'92s your intestines or a demon.\
The pain in your stomach becomes unbearable. You can\'92t walk. You\'92re doubled over, gasping, sweat pouring down your face. You plead with your partner to call 911.\
When the paramedics arrive, your partner has to spend twenty minutes convincing them that you\'92re not nine months pregnant and in labor. The bloating is so extreme you look like you\'92ve swallowed a basketball. Your skin is stretched tight \'97 so tight you\'92re surprised you don\'92t burst into stretch marks.\
They try and fail to find a vein. You tell them it\'92s always like this, that you need ultrasound guidance, but they insist they know what they\'92re doing. Eventually, they give up and jab you with an intramuscular injection of fentanyl. It hits bone. You scream.\
The bruising is immediate and deep. You won\'92t be able to lift your arm high enough to put on a shirt for a month.\
You go to the ER.\
Triage takes hours. You crochet a queen-sized blanket while waiting for a hallway gurney. You\'92re offered Tylenol, a lidocaine patch (for your stomach), and eye rolls. The pain is upper gastric spasms. The patch is for muscle pain. You tell them. They nod and hand you a psych eval form.\
Eventually, someone wheels you off for abdominal X-rays. Standing up is nearly impossible, but no one seems to care. You\'92re hunched over in pain, clinging to the imaging table, and still get reprimanded for being dramatic. They\'92re looking for a small bowel obstruction, even though your chart says you\'92re on two daily bowel preps. The radiologist notes say \'93excessive gas and diarrhea.\'94 You whisper, \'93Idiots.\'94\
\cb2 Later, they wheel you to get another CT scan with contrast \'97 your sixth in as many weeks. You do the mental math on the radiation. If the illness doesn\'92t kill you, the scans might. You pull up the radiology report on your phone and feed it into ChatGPT. It swears: \'93WHAT THE HELL ARE THEY EVEN LOOKING FOR? THIS IS LIKE MEDICAL BINGO WITH A SHOTGUN.\'94\cb1 \
You\'92re wheeled back to the hallway. Still no room.\
You try to make it to the bathroom, but the bed alarm shrieks. A nurse yanks you back. You shit your pants and vomit into your lap. You ring the call button every two hours, begging for help. Each time, you\'92re told, \'93Your nurse will be there soon.\'94 They never are.\
At 7 p.m., the shift changes. The nurses who tried to help are replaced by ones who won\'92t even make eye contact. You\'92re too tired to re-explain everything, and too afraid of being labeled difficult if you do.\
\cb3 A psychiatrist finally arrives and interrupts your story with one of his own: \'93I once couldn\'92t stop burping for two weeks. Turned out it was stress from Chipotle. You know the gut-brain connection, right?\'94\
You stare at him.\
He nods and scribbles into your chart. The nurse comes in next with Benadryl and Ativan \'97 the usual cocktail. \'93The doctor ordered it for your comfort,\'94 she says. You ask for something else \'97 maybe something that helps you sleep through the pain, or an anti-anxiety med to help you cope. She labels you drug-seeking. It\'92s written in your chart.\
Later, she comes back to your bed, this time without meds but with a monologue. She pulls up her sleeve to reveal a full sleeve of colorful tattoos \'97 mandalas, phoenixes, celestial bodies inked across skin like a map of forced transformation. She tells you how trauma made her whole, how pain taught her to heal, how every needle and heartbreak became art. She recommends tattoos for you. Says her $500 juice cleanse and charcoal pills were game-changers. Tells you how she swears by her $30-per-class spin regimen, and that it cured her 'toxin overload' \'97 though she can\'92t really explain what toxins are. That mindfulness healed her gut.\cb1 \
You want to scream.\
Instead, you nod. Because if you challenge her, you\'92ll be labeled again. Maybe even restrained. And right now, staying still is the only defense you have left.\
When you\'92re not sedated, you\'92re vomiting. When you\'92re not vomiting, you\'92re waiting.\
You post a TikTok from the hallway. It goes viral.\
You call it: 
\f1\b \'93Live from Gurney Gulag: DIY IVs, Paper Pants, and the Stench of Neglect\'94
\f0\b0  \'97 filmed from your side-lying position, with an emesis bag in one hand and a crochet hook in the other. You narrate it deadpan: \'93Day 3 of being marinated in my own medical mystery. So far I\'92ve collected 12 bruises, 2 missed veins, 1 existential crisis, and zero functioning IVs.\'94\
A nurse in triage had insisted you could be stuck \'93just fine\'94 despite your warning about needing ultrasound-guided access. She tried anyway. Missed. Tried again. And again. After the fifth miss, she sighed and said, \'93Well, someone\'92ll come with the ultrasound eventually.\'94\
Hours passed. The tech finally arrived with a clunky machine and a look of practiced pity. They dug around your collapsed arm until the vein finally gave way \'97 but by then, your hand looked like overripe fruit.\
