\cf0 But the story isn't over. Not even close.\
You're awoken at 3 a.m. by a phlebotomist jabbing at your hand \'97 the only visible vein left. They miss three times, draw too little, and promise to come back. They do. Thirty minutes later.\
At 6 a.m., another nurse wakes you up for meds. You haven't slept. You can't.\
You're still on a bed alarm. You still have no nurse call button. You're still in scrubs with a giant stain. They give you a menu. You laugh. As if you could eat. As if you weren\'92t NPO and vomiting up even water. You ask for mouth swabs. They forget.\
The nurse ghosts you. The same one who rolled her eyes when you asked for help reaching the bathroom. You beg. Still nothing.\
\cb2 Eventually, a security guard is stationed at your door. He\'92s bored. He brags about his Kanye West merch, shows you grainy photos of his new sneakers, and insists you\'92d be healed if you 'stopped resisting the Lord\'92s plan.'\
Then he offers unsolicited health advice. 'You ever try apple cider vinegar and sea moss gel? Cleared up my auntie's lupus.'\cb1 \
You try to shift positions.\
'Yeah, pain is real, but it\'92s also a choice,' he says. 'I had a sore back once from doing deadlifts wrong. Chiropractor changed my life.'\
You vomit just to make him stop.\
When you try to go to the bathroom \'97 in agony, desperate \'97 you\'92re yanked back by your arm. You shit yourself again. You\'92re left to sit in it until someone remembers you exist. They never bring clean clothes. Your emesis bag pile reaches Mount Everest levels.\
You\'92re labeled. Again. This time for \'93behavior.\'94\
\cb5 At discharge, your Uber refuses the ride. You collapse on the bench. You text your partner, even though you know asking him to come will flare his condition. He comes anyway. Because he always does.\
You crash into bed. He hooks up your pump. The feeding tube dangles like a lifeline \'97 except this one is full of the wrong formula, pumped at a rate designed for a body that isn\'92t yours. You vomit almost immediately. The nausea coils in your gut like barbed wire.\cb1 \
You reach for the nurse call button \'97 only to remember it never existed. You were on a hallway gurney. Then a bed with a broken cord. Now home with a tube you can\'92t tolerate and a body that refuses to comply.\
You email your team. You beg for help. For a port. For anything.\
No reply.\
\cb3 You can\'92t even sip water without retching. Your lips are peeling. Your joints scream when you move. You start keeping a tally of how many towels you\'92ve ruined \'97 bile, formula, blood. Five loads of laundry a day. Sometimes ten. The smell never quite leaves.\cb1 \
\cb2 You sit there in your paper scrubs, still stained from the hospital, because no one thought to find your clothes. You wrap a blanket around yourself like armor. You rock, and breathe, and whisper through cracked lips, \'93This can\'92t be it.\'94\
And still, no one comes.\
You want it to end.\
But he\'92s there. And you\'92re still breathing. And somewhere, someone else is crocheting their own ER blanket, waiting for a nurse who will never come.\
You get it now.\
And maybe, just maybe, you can help them survive too.\cb1 \
